And I feel like the R Validation Hub has been so critical in the adoption of open source in the

00:04:51.839 --> 00:04:57.839
drug development space for helping to establish understandings around validation and this risk

00:04:57.839 --> 00:05:02.239
based approach for people watching. Why don't you give a little bit of background around the R

00:05:02.239 --> 00:05:06.799
Validation Hub and the work that they've done? Okay. Yeah. So R Validation Hub, I think they

00:05:06.799 --> 00:05:13.519
came out of the R Pharma conference back in 2018, if I'm not mistaken. And it's a collaborative

00:05:13.519 --> 00:05:20.959
among several pharma orgs of approximately 10 or so that are supporting the adoption of R in a

00:05:20.959 --> 00:05:27.519
regulatory space. Oftentimes they are including the FDA in what they're doing so that they're

00:05:27.519 --> 00:05:33.119
getting good quality feedback from some sort of regulatory agency. And a lot of organizations

00:05:33.119 --> 00:05:40.320
sort of subscribe to our content. And I would say the primary driver, at least early on,

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:45.040
was our white paper that we published. And so the white paper basically says that

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:51.279
every organization is going to have a different definition of what validation means. And they're

00:05:51.279 --> 00:05:58.399
going to have different risk tolerances towards what is considered a quality piece of software

00:05:58.399 --> 00:06:05.920
or a not quality piece of software. So in that vein, the R Validation Hub says that, hey,

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:13.200
there's certain quality metrics that we can all sort of define and not necessarily agree upon,

00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:18.720
like which ones are more important to you. But we can use these to sort of define our own level

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:24.480
of risk. And then from there, you can use that as evidence to document that your software that

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:30.799
you're using for your clinical trial analysis is reliable. And I think one thing that's so

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:36.000
awesome is that the R Validation Hub generated this white paper that helps provide general

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.959
information around this risk-based approach. But then the organization took it a step farther

00:06:40.959 --> 00:06:45.920
and created tools that helps organization implement that white paper. So the risk metric

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:51.279
package, the risk assessment app that you work on. So tell people about those two.

00:06:51.839 --> 00:06:56.399
Yeah, I would say so cornerstone to the white paper is definitely the risk metric package.

00:06:56.399 --> 00:07:02.480
So it's essentially is an R package that helps you evaluate other R packages,

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:10.559
like software quality based off of certain domains. So like the package maintenance

00:07:10.559 --> 00:07:16.000
sort of domain, the community engagement, and then also like the rigor of testing that's

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:21.600
performed. So to give an example, I think that for testing, there's metrics that

00:07:22.959 --> 00:07:29.519
the package will define, such as code coverage. So that's a big one, especially for a lot of

00:07:29.519 --> 00:07:33.040
regulatory environments is they want to make sure that the software that you're using has

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:38.640
been tested really well and that the security is top notch. So risk metric will allow you to

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:42.880
do that. It'll also tell you like, you know, how many downloads does this package have per year?

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:47.920
Is it really popular? Does it have reverse dependency? So are other packages depending

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:53.760
on this package? And then software maintenance best practices are stuff like, does it have good

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:58.959
documentation? Is there a website? Is there vignettes that describe how to use the code?

00:08:00.079 --> 00:08:05.679
And I feel like that package helps provide the metrics and then to help provide some reporting

00:08:05.679 --> 00:08:10.559
and clarity to IT and people throughout the organization, you created a shiny app that

00:08:10.559 --> 00:08:15.359
exposes some of this information. And so organizations can say, these are the packages

00:08:15.359 --> 00:08:19.600
that we've included and these are the things that we want information about. And what's it been like

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:25.279
to maintain and support that package? Yeah. Yeah. So it's been a long going effort. Like there's

00:08:25.279 --> 00:08:29.279
been tons of contributors over the years that have been sort of building these tools up.

00:08:29.279 --> 00:08:34.799
I should have mentioned that from the get go. So I came in when the app was already created

00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:40.559
and I've just as a individual contributor, I'm starting to, you know, knock out some GitHub

00:08:40.559 --> 00:08:46.960
